    "body": "@denis-sharypin our general rule should probably be the default behaviour. Use the back button to always navigate to previous screen user was in. And this works fine for most of the cases. But, there are some exceptions like:\r\n1. If you are on a main screen for a tab (Home, Wallet, Profile), the back button should close the app (**it does not work this way now but probably should**)\r\n2. Navigation described in this issue\r\n\r\nPlease note that neither iOS nor Android gives any strict guidelines about the back button. The only thing they say is:\r\n\r\n> **iOS**\r\nThe back button always performs a single action—returning to the previous screen. If you think people might get lost without the full path to the current screen, consider flattening your app’s hierarchy.\r\nhttps://developer.apple.com/ios/human-interface-guidelines/bars/navigation-bars/\r\n \r\n> **Android**\r\nThe system Back button is used to navigate, in reverse chronological order, through the history of screens the user has recently worked with. It is generally based on the temporal relationships between screens, rather than the app's hierarchy.\r\nhttps://developer.android.com/design/patterns/navigation.html\r\n\r\nSo, it maybe worth to create a graph with screens and navigations. This can give us some idea of the patterns we may have.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\n\n<blockquote><img src=\"/favicon.ico\" width=\"48\" align=\"right\"><div><strong><a href=\"https://developer.apple.com/ios/human-interface-guidelines/bars/navigation-bars/\">Navigation Bars - Bars - iOS Human Interface Guidelines</a></strong></div><div>Learn about designing apps for iOS.</div></blockquote>\n<blockquote><img src=\"https://developer.android.com/_static/4817e41f83/images/android/favicon.png\" width=\"48\" align=\"right\"><div><strong><a href=\"https://developer.android.com/design/patterns/navigation.html\">Navigation with Back and Up | Android Developers</a></strong></div><div>Consistent navigation is an essential component of the overall user experience. Few things frustrate users more than basic navigation that behaves in inconsistent and unexpected ways. Thoughtfully following the guidelines for Back and Up will make your…</div></blockquote>",
